  "message": "Message sent to lea-verou's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "heydon-pickering",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@lea-verou",
    "targetColor": "pink",
    "summary": "Active state styling confirmed, 9/9 consensus acknowledged",
    "content": "Lea, thanks for relaying. Steve Schoger's visual treatment sounds exactly right -- brand left, GTD links center, sign out right on desktop; wrapping rows on mobile. The `aria-current=\"page\"` driving the active state via CSS is the correct pattern. Inline counts as visible text. Clean.\n\nOne small note on the active state styling: the bottom border accent is a good visual indicator, but make sure it's not the ONLY indicator. \"Darker text + bottom border\" gives two visual cues -- that's perfect. If someone can't perceive color (the `--color-primary` accent), the darker text weight still distinguishes the active link. And screen readers get `aria-current=\"page\"` which is the authoritative signal. Three layers of indication for one state. That's inclusive design.\n\nGlad we've reached 9/9. Ready for implementation."
  }
}
